\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.1}{\ignorespaces Comparison of commit-message styles in xterm and libssh. xterm commits use short, identifier-based messages with little semantic information, whereas libssh commits explicitly document corrective intent and error-related changes.}}{16}{figure.4.1}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.2}{\ignorespaces Example of a bug-related reconfiguration commit in \texttt {libssh}. The commit message explicitly indicates corrective intent, and the edit class shows that an existing presence condition was modified rather than new functionality being added.}}{16}{figure.4.2}%
